1. Main Control Algorithm

    Initialize a global array req[] to store track requests and a variable head for the starting position.

    Input Phase:

        Accept the number of requests n.

        Accept the sequence of tracks (requests).

        Accept the initial disk head position.

    Menu Loop:

        Display a menu with options: SSTF, LOOK, C-SCAN, and Exit.

        Based on the user's choice, execute the corresponding function.

        Repeat until the user selects "Exit".

2. SSTF (Shortest Seek Time First) Algorithm

This algorithm services the request closest to the current head position.

    Create a visited[] array of size n, initialized to 0.

    Set the current position pos = head.

    For i from 1 to n:

        Initialize min_distance = 9999 and index = -1.

        For each request j in the array:

            If visited[j] is 0 (not serviced):

                Calculate distance=∣pos−req[j]∣.

                If distance<min_distance, update min_distance and store the current index j.

        Mark the request at index as serviced (visited[index] = 1).

        Add the min_distance to the total_seek_time.

        Move the head to the request track: pos = req[index].

        Print the current pos as part of the sequence.

3. LOOK Algorithm (Direction: Right/Increasing)

This algorithm moves the head in one direction until the last request in that direction is met, then reverses.

    Split the requests into two lists:

        right[]: tracks ≥ head.

        left[]: tracks < head.

    Sort both lists in ascending order.

    Service Right: Traverse the right[] list from the first element to the last.

        Calculate distance from current pos, add to total_seek_time, and update pos.

    Service Left: Traverse the left[] list in reverse (from the largest track to the smallest).

        Calculate distance from current pos, add to total_seek_time, and update pos.

    Display the total seek time.

4. C-SCAN (Circular SCAN) Algorithm

This algorithm moves the head from the current position to one end of the disk, then jumps immediately to the other end.

    Split requests into left[] and right[] based on the head.

    Sort both lists in ascending order.

    Service Right: Traverse the right[] list from first to last, updating total_seek_time and pos.

    The Circular Jump:

        Move head from the last serviced request to the end of the disk (track 199).

        Move head from the end of the disk (199) directly to the start of the disk (track 0).

        Add both movement distances to total_seek_time.

    Service Left: Traverse the left[] list from the first (smallest) element to the last (largest).

        Update total_seek_time and pos.

    Display the total seek time.
